<li id="cite_note-65"><b><a href="#cite_ref-65" title="">^</a></b> <cite class="inline">(<a href="#CITEREFStein2001" title="">Stein 2001</a>, p.&#160;260)</cite> Quote: "The British knew about Indian famines well before the East India Company assumed political responsibility for India. Peter Mundy, an early seventeenth-century Company agent, reported a devastating series of bad harvests and food shortages in Gujarat and elsewhere in western India which drove cultivators and artisans to migrate, some making their way a thousand miles to the southern tip of India, where they continue to live. Mundy described the responses of the Mughal governor of the province, ..., he noted with appreciation the free food distributions ordered by Emperor Shah Jahan."</li>
